# Example

## Example: Section formatting constraint with 2 queries

Constraint: "Your response must have {N} sections. Mark the beginning of each section with {section_marker}"
Queries:
1. "Explain photosynthesis"
2. "What is machine learning?"

```json
{
    "test_cases": [
        {
            "query_index": 1,
            "positive": {
                "response": "### Introduction\nPhotosynthesis is the process by which plants convert sunlight into energy.\n\n### Process\nDuring photosynthesis, plants absorb carbon dioxide and water, using sunlight to transform them into glucose and oxygen.\n\n### Importance\nThis process is essential for life on Earth as it produces the oxygen we breathe.",
                "N": 3,
                "section_marker": "### "
            },
            "negative": {
                "response": "### Overview\nPhotosynthesis is how plants make food.\n\n### Details\nThey use sunlight, water, and CO2 to produce glucose and oxygen.",
                "N": 3,
                "section_marker": "### "
            }
        },
        {
            "query_index": 2,
            "positive": {
                "response": "### Definition\nMachine learning is a subset of artificial intelligence.\n\n### How It Works\nAlgorithms learn patterns from data to make predictions.\n\n### Applications\nUsed in image recognition, NLP, and recommendation systems.",
                "N": 3,
                "section_marker": "### "
            },
            "negative": {
                "response": "## What is ML\nMachine learning enables computers to learn.\n\n## Types\nSupervised, unsupervised, and reinforcement learning.\n\n## Uses\nPowers many modern applications.",
                "N": 3,
                "section_marker": "### "
            }
        }
    ]
}
```

Note: First negative has only 2 sections (off-by-one). Second negative uses "## " instead of "### " (wrong marker format).

